{{Criminal defenses}}
'''''Per minas''''', in [[Great Britain|British]] [[common law]], to engage in behavior "by means of menaces or threats".<ref>[http://www.clickdocs.co.uk/glossary/per-minas.htm Clickdocs web site]</ref>
The term [[Etymology|comes from]] [[Latin]].<ref>[http://www.sanjeev.net/latin/latin-phrases-starting-with-p-07.html List of Latin legal phrases].</ref>
''Per minas'' [[Legal history|has been used]] as a [[Criminal defense|defense]] of [[duress]] to certain [[crime]]s, as affecting the element of ''[[mens rea]]''.<ref>[http://www.springerlink.com/content/p3g0kt866r448302/ Duress ''per minas'' as a defense (sic.) to crime], from ''Law and Philosophy'', 185-195 (August 1982).</ref><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/3304503 JSTO site], from ''A Consideration of What Amounts to Duress Per Minas at Law'', in the American Law Register, Vol. 23, No. 4, (April 1875), pp. 201-207.</ref> [[William Blackstone]], the often-cited [[judge]] and [[legal scholar]], addressed the use of "duress ''per minas''" under the category of self-defense as a means of securing the "right of personal security", that is, the [[right of self-defense]].<ref>[http://press-pubs.uchicago.edu/founders/documents/amendIXs1.html], citing Blackstone, (I)(2) (1765).</ref>
The classic case involves a person who is [[blackmail]]ed into robbing a [[bank]].
In [[contract law]], Blackstone used ''per minas'' to describe the defense of [[duress]], as affecting the element of '''contract intent''', '''mutual assent''', or [[meeting of the minds]].<ref>[http://www.law-dictionary.org/PER+MINAS.asp?q=PER+MINAS Law-dictionary-com], citing I Blackstone's Commentaries 131.</ref><ref>[http://onlinedictionary.datasegment.com/word/per+minas Online Law dictionary], citing Bouvier's Law Dictionary, Revised 6th Ed (1856).</ref>
